mikeb@gl.umbc.edu (Mike J. Bell) writes:

>I've got a question.  I've read how PGP and RIPEM support sending a
>message to multiple users->multiple keys.

>I assume that this means encoding the message n times, once for each
>recipient.  So therefore, if you don't have this scheme integrated
>with your mailer, you have to send out a message that's n times longer
>than it would be for one recipient, no?

No.  In the case of PGP (I dunno from RIPEM), what happens is that the
file is encrypted with IDEA, and the IDEA key is encrypted with RSA.
So only the RSA-encrypted IDEA key is repeated n times.

